04978nam a22007695i 9780813562834DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013010366  a97808135628347 a10.36019/97808135628342doi  a(DE-B1597)529179  a(OCoLC)1164131508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHQ1031b.T46 2014 4aHQ1031b.T46 2014 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a305.892/40732231 aThompson, Jennifer A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJewish on Their Own Terms :bHow Intermarried Couples are Changing American Judaism /cJennifer A. Thompson. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Defining Judaism by Debating Intermarriage -- t2. American Contradictions: Conversations about Self and Community -- t3. "What You Are" and "What's in Your Heart" -- t4. Translating Jewish Experience -- t5. Sovereign Selves in a Fractured Community -- t6. Moving Forward, Inconclusively: The Crisis of Jewish Identity -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver half of all American Jewish children are being raised by intermarried parents. This demographic group will have a tremendous impact on American Judaism as it is lived and practiced in the coming decades. To date, however, in both academic studies about Judaism and in the popular imagination, such children and their parents remain marginal. Jennifer A. Thompson takes a different approach. In Jewish on Their Own Terms, she tells the stories of intermarried couples, the rabbis and other Jewish educators who work with them, and the conflicting public conversations about intermarriage among American Jews. Thompson notes that in the dominant Jewish cultural narrative, intermarriage symbolizes individualism and assimilation. Talking about intermarriage allows American Jews to discuss their anxieties about remaining distinctively Jewish despite their success in assimilating into American culture. In contrast, Thompson uses ethnography to describe the compelling concerns of all of these parties and places their anxieties firmly within the context of American religious culture and morality. She explains how American and traditional Jewish gender roles converge to put non-Jewish women in charge of raising Jewish children. Interfaith couples are like other Americans in often harboring contradictory notions of individual autonomy, universal religious truths, and obligations to family and history. Focusing on the lived experiences of these families, Jewish on Their OwnTerms provides a complex and insightful portrait of intermarried couples and the new forms of American Judaism that they are constructing.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aInterfaith marriagezUnited States. 0aIntermarriagezUnited States. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzUnited States. 0aJewszUnited StatesxCultural assimilation. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aJudaismzUnited Statesy21st century. 0aMarriagexReligious aspectsxJudaism. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813562834.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013